2. WHAT is commonly, in a popular sense, called reason, and is so much recommended in moral discourses, is nothing but a general and a calm passion, which takes a comprehensive and distant view of its object, and actuates the will, without exciting any sensible emotion. A man, we say, is diligent in his profession from rea
son; that is, from a calm desire of riches and a fortune. A man adheres to justice from reason;
that is, from a calm regard to a character with himself and others.
